text:
Hi Drew,
re: what type of database, from the readme:
&gt; relational (has tables with typed columns and foreign keys)

re: tree-structured queries; they are GraphQL-style, but with a more SQL-like syntax. Here's an example from the readme, slightly reindented:
```MANY blog_posts {
  id, title, body,
  comments: MANY comments {
    id, body,
    author: ONE users {
      name
    },
  }
}```
…and yes, as shown in the readme, the response is a whole tree as JSON.

re: how to do live queries: this code path: :stuck_out_tongue: <https://github.com/vilterp/treesql/blob/master/pkg/live_queries.go#L94-L101>
Basically, when a live query is first run, it saves "listeners" in a special data structure in memory. Later, when writes come in, we look up those listeners, find live queries interested in that write, and push it out to them.

There's nothing that makes it fundamentally easier to do that in a document store than in a relational database. CockroachDB (where I work) is built on top of a key-value store, as are document DBs, and we have one of the building blocks of live queries: changefeeds (<https://www.cockroachlabs.com/docs/stable/create-changefeed.html>), a way of getting a feed of writes going into the DB. The tricky part is mapping these writes to the queries that would be interested in them — i.e. "a comment with blog post id 5 was inserted =&gt; these 11 queries covered blog post 5, so they'd want to know about this"

elements.text:
MANY blog_posts {
  id, title, body,
  comments: MANY comments {
    id, body,
    author: ONE users {
      name
    },
  }
}
